man: ethnic name for someone from Poland.","Americanized form of Jewish   Polak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pogue","meanings":["Irish (Cavan): shortened form of the Scottish name   Pollock   1, Gaelicized as <b>Polóc</b>, later assimilated to the Irish word <i>póg</i> ‘kiss’."]},{"name":"Pollick","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Pollock  . This surname is rare in Britain.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Polič</b>, Croatian and Serbian <b>Polić</b> (see   Polich  ). Compare   Polick  ."]},{"name":"Palk","meanings":["English (Devon): shortened form of   Pollock  , with unrounding of the vowel to give <i>Palk</i>. Compare   Polk   and also   Pulford  . Derivation from a shortened form of the Middle English personal names <i>Palcok</i> and <i>Palkin</i> (pet forms of <i>Paul</i>) is formally possible, but no evidence has been found to substantiate this."]},{"name":"Paulk","meanings":["English (Devon) and Scottish: shortened form of   Pollock  . The Scottish name is a variant of   Polk  .","Altered form of a German surname, possibly   Paulke  ."]},{"name":"Polk","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Pollock  .","Sorbian (<b>Półk</b> and <b>Pólk</b>): probably from a short form of a personal name based on Old Slavic <i>plъkъ</i> ‘crowd, army’ (see   Polka   3).","East German (of Slavic origin): variant of   Polke  ."]},{"name":"Pollok","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire): variant of   Pollock  ."]},{"name":"Polak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Miroslaw, Zbigniew, Boguslawa, Dorota, Jacek, Andrzej, Bogdan, Eugeniusz, Grzegorz, Irena, Jerzy, Jozef.","Polish and Jewish (Ashkenazic); Czech, Slovak, and Hungarian (<b>Polák</b>, Slovak also <b>Poľák</b>): ethnic name for someone from Poland (Polish <i>Polak</i>, Slovak archaic and Czech <i>Polák</i>). In the case of the Ashkenazic name, the reference is to a Jew from Poland. This surname is also found in Germany, where it is also of Sorbian origin (see 3 below), and in the Netherlands. Compare   Poliak  ,   Poljak  , and   Polyak  .","Slovenian and Croatian: topographic name for someone who lived in open country, derived from <i>polje</i> ‘field’, or a habitational name for someone from any of numerous places called Polje, named with this word. It may also be e.g. an occupational name for a field guard (see   Poljak  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henery","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrupted from Henry."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Henery de Pollock was born in 1190, in Renfrewshire, Scotland, his father, Robert de Pollock III, was 38 and his mother, Isabella, was 14. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1260, in his hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1190–1260":"1190–1260","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1230–1295":"1230–1295","1152–1219":"1152–1219","1176–Female":"1176–Surnud","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1152":"1152","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1219":"1219","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1190–1260":"1190–1260","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1230–1295":"1230–1295","1152–1219":"1152–1219","1176–Female":"1176–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1152":"1152","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1219":"1219","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1190–1260":"1190–1260","1215–Male":"1215–Décédé","1230–1295":"1230–1295","1152–1219":"1152–1219","1176–Female":"1176–Décédée","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1176":"1176","1230":"1230